title: For Sale:  New IRIS240 NightSpotter Hand Held Thermal Camera - 384x288 19mm - Special Sale Price Thru 9/3
postcontent: IRIS240 Nightspotter 384 x 288 19mm (Note that many IRIS241 models are mislabeled online as the 240 and you can tell the difference as only the 240 has 384x288 resolution with a 19mm lens)I purchased this unit in April/May of 2016 for $2700 or nearly  $3000 with tax and shipping.  I had thought that this could be a fun toy to play with when camping, hiking, or other activities.  Since then however I have used this not once having forgotten to bring it on the two occasions where I may have had a chance to use it.  Bottom line is that this was a cool, albeit expensive toy, but I'm simply not getting enough/any use out of it.  The only time I did actually briefly use it was when I opened the box to take pictures.  I was very impressed.I have been able to use several other thermal devices on other occasions with friends and I found this IRIS 240 to be far superior to most in a comperable price range and on par with a number that I was able to personally play around with, which were selling at sometimes as much as $3000 - $5000.  Below are some other thermal imaging units that I used and their specs so that you can get at least some idea of how they stack up though if you can compare them head to head, I would highly recomend doing so.IRIS240 384x288 19mm Features:19mm LensField of View: 28.36 degrees x 21.46 degreesZoom: 2X, 4X and standard 1XSpectral Range: 8~14umRefresh Rate:  25HzEnvironmental Rating: IP66Composite Video Output8-Hour Battery OperationBuilt In LED TorchVehicle Object Detection:  2380m detection, 500m recognition (these are very conservative as I found magification to enable detection and identification ranges to be far greater)The IRIS240 Nightspotter is a great new thermal imaging camera that can be used for a wide variety of tasks.  Please visit the IRIS website for further info.I did a great deal of research before purchasing this unit and tried out many competitng devices as a part of my research in addition to having used some other devices with friends on prior occasions.  The unit that I found most similar in all aspects including design, learning curve, button config., specs, and more was the Night Optics Explorer 320 (384x288) Thermal Camera (1x | 19mm) with LED.  Many of the specs for this unit are the same as the IRIS though the price is $4500, though you can sometimes find them on sale for somewhere between $3500 and $4000.I found the IRIS240 to be far superior to the majority of the lower end and comparably priced FLIR defices (roughly $2000 - $3500).  These are the FLIR TK Scout Series, The FLIR Scout II Series, and the FLIR Scout III Series.  These FLIR units have a refresh rate of just 9 Hz (versus 25 Hz for the IRIS240), a battery life of just 4-5 hrs. (8+ hrs for the IRIS240), and a field of view for these units range from 17x13 degrees on the low end (FLIR Scout III 240) to the highest being 24-18 degrees (FLIR Scout III 240).  This compares to 28.5x21.5 degrees FOV for the IRIS240.  Magnification or zoom ability was also less attractive with some providing fixed magnification of 3x-6x but no 1x magnification, while most provided 1-2X magnification, and some provided 4X.  In addition to the FLIR product series mentioned above, below are a couple other units I've been able to test at one time or another:Pulsar Quantum Thermal Imaging Scope - $2500 to $3500Night Optics Thermal Imaging TM7X - $2500+

title: For Sale:  custom stiller tac 30 7 wsm  / 300 wsm package
postcontent: Rifle was built by Dave Jaffe out of Bozeman, Mt. Stiller tac 30 action which has been milled to perfectly accept a wyatts center feed extended mag box and 20 moa rail. McMillan a3 stock glass and pillar bedded. Jewel hvt trigger, remington 700 aluminum bottom metal, thunder beast muzzle brake and two barrels. All metal is coated in coyote brown duracoat except for the 7mm barrel, that is still stainless. The 4 ammo boxes shown in the picture are also included. Bipod and scope/rings are not included. .300 WSM: Round count 135. Ace 22" 9 twist remington varmiter contour. Comes with (52) 4x fired, (35) 5x fired, and (10) 6x fired norma 300 wsm brass. All brass has been recently trimmed, necks turned to .015", and annealed. Also comes with redding completion seater die, redding type s full length sizing die, redding type s neck sizing die, and a wilson hand seating die. No bushings are included. 7mm-300wsm: Round count 234. I chose this caliber instead of the 7 wsm due to brass availability. I am using high quality readily available norma 300 wsm brass. I had the gunsmith run a 7 wsm reamer until it would headspace off the 300 wsm gauges, meaning it has a shorter neck just like the 7 wsm. Once cases are necked down, I trim the necks back .039" and turn the necks to .015". I was getting 3000 fps with a 180 berger hybrid with h1000. This is a broughton 5.75 contour fluted 9 twist at 26". Included with this barrel is (60) 2x fired, and (38) 3x fired prepped, trimmed, turned, and annealed brass. Redding 7 wsm competition seater and a custom redding 7mm-300wsm full length sizing die that I had Dave open the neck up to .312" which is the bushing size I was using with the 300 wsm type s neck die. Also if the buyer wants to make things easy, I could have Dave run the 7 wsm reamer all the way in to make it a 7 wsm chamber. This whole package comes out to about $5700
